So first I need to solve the formula for area of a circle because that's what I need the diameter of. The formula for the area of a circle is $\pi(\text{radius})^2$. So to find the radius, I do the following work: \begin{aligned} \pi &= (\text{radius})^2\;\;\;\text{Since Area} = \pi(\text{radius})^2 \\\\ \text{radius}&= \sqrt{\pi} \end{aligned}
<answer> Now that I have the radius, I use it to solve for diameter. The formula for diameter is $2(\text{radius})$. So substituting my radius out, I can easily just say: \begin{aligned} \text{diameter}&= 2(\text{radius})\\\\ \text{diameter}&= 2(\sqrt{\pi})\\\\ \text{You could simplify this to:}\\\\ \text{diameter}&= \sqrt{4\pi} \end{aligned}
</answer>

